Common Interview Questions
1. Why use HashMap?

HashMap stores the frequency of each element and provides average O(1) insertion and lookup.

2. Why is the bucket array size nums.length + 1?

Because the maximum frequency of any element cannot exceed the total number of elements in the array.

3. Why is Bucket Sort better than sorting?

Sorting takes:

O(n log n)

Bucket Sort groups elements directly by frequency and avoids sorting.

Overall complexity becomes:

O(n)
4. Why traverse the buckets from right to left?

Higher indices represent higher frequencies.

Traversing backwards ensures we collect the most frequent elements first.

5. Why can one bucket contain multiple elements?

Multiple numbers may have the same frequency.

Example:

1 → 2

2 → 2

3 → 2

Then

bucket[2] = [1,2,3]
Common Mistakes

❌ Creating the bucket array with map.size() + 1

Correct:

new ArrayList[nums.length + 1]

❌ Initializing only map.size() buckets

Correct:

for(int i=0;i<bucket.length;i++)

❌ Forgetting to initialize each bucket

Incorrect:

bucket[i].add(...)

before

bucket[i] = new ArrayList<>();

This causes a NullPointerException.

❌ Forgetting to stop after collecting k elements.

Interview Explanation (1 Minute)

"I first use a HashMap to count the frequency of every element. Instead of sorting the frequencies, I observe that the maximum possible frequency of any element is equal to the array size. Based on this observation, I create a bucket array where each index represents a frequency, and each bucket stores all elements having that frequency. Finally, I traverse the buckets from the highest frequency to the lowest, collecting elements until I have k results. This avoids sorting and achieves an overall time complexity of O(n)."

